  doi = {10.2307/1592460},
  urldate = {2022-09-12},
  abstract = {Detecting Salmonella enteritidis contamination in eggs has become the c nerstone of many programs for reducing egg-borne disease transmission, but egg cultur is time consuming and laborious. Preliminary screening tests are thus generally applie minimize the number of flocks from which eggs must be cultured. The usefulness of tests is directly proportional to both their detection sensitivity and their ability to pred the likelihood of egg contamination. In the present study, samples were collected for 24 after groups of laying hens were orally inoculated with S. enteritidis. Eggs from each were cultured for S. enteritidis in the contents and samples of egg yolk were diluted tested for specific antibodies to S. enteritidis flagella using both experimental and comm cially available enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) methods. Samples of void feces were also collected regularly from each bird and cultured for S. enteritidis. Althou fecal shedding and egg yolk antibody production followed opposite patterns over time (f shedding was decreasing as egg yolk antibody titers were increasing), tests for both parame were effective in predicting whether particular hens would lay contaminated eggs. Am hens that laid at least one egg contaminated by S. enteritidis, 82\% were detected as infec by fecal culturing and 96\% by the experimental egg yolk ELISA test. Using easily colle samples, egg yolk antibody testing offers a rapid and effective screening method for ide fying S. enteritidis-infected laying flocks that might lay contaminated eggs.},
  langid = {english},
  file = {C:\Users\rebeca.falcao\Zotero\storage\WZJ32GUA\Gast et al. - 1997 - Applying Tests for Specific Yolk Antibodies to Pre.pdf}
